To get a free SSL certificate for your HTTP server on Nginx running in an Azure Container Instance, Let's Encrypt is a great choice. First, you need your domain name pointing to the Azure instance and ensure ports 80 and 443 are open.

Start by installing Certbot, a tool to help you get and renew those free SSL certificates—either by adding it to your container image or using a temporary Docker container if it’s not already there. When running Certbot, you might prefer the DNS challenge if your IP changes often, or go the simpler route with the HTTP challenge, which spins up a server to handle requests. Here’s a quick command with the HTTP challenge:

```bash
certbot certonly --webroot -w /var/www/html -d yourdomain.com -d www.yourdomain.com
```

Make sure '-w' links to your Nginx web root.

Next, tweak your Nginx configuration file to accept the SSL certificate. Look for a file like `/etc/nginx/nginx.conf` and edit it:

```nginx
server {
    listen 443 ssl;
    server_name yourdomain.com www.yourdomain.com;

    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/yourdomain.com/fullchain.pem;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/yourdomain.com/privkey.pem;

    location / {
        # Your configuration
    }
}

server {
    listen 80;
    server_name yourdomain.com www.yourdomain.com;
    return 301 https://$server_name$request_uri;
}
```

Change 'yourdomain.com' with your actual domain.

On renewing, these certificates last 90 days. Make sure to automate renewal using a cron job, for instance:

```bash
0 0 * * 0 certbot renew --nginx
```

Finally, keep an eye on your Nginx and Certbot logs for issues. They’re usually in `/var/log/nginx/` and `/var/log/letsencrypt/`.

Extra tip: Consider using Azure Key Vault or Azure Blob Storage for managing certificates. A sidecar container or init container in Kubernetes can help with this.

That's pretty much it—a general guide that you might need to tweak based on your specific setup.

