Creating a simple landing page with a mail form using Next.js and getting it on Vercel is a good start. So, first, make sure you've got Node.js and npm on your machine. You'd grab them from nodejs.org if they're not there.

Then, kick off a new Next.js project. Fire up your terminal and run:

```bash
npx create-next-app my-landing-page
```

Change `my-landing-page` to whatever you want to call your project. Next, jump over to your new project directory:

```bash
cd my-landing-page
```

Inside, you'll be working in the `pages` directory. Open up `index.js` and replace the content with a basic landing page. Here's a simple start:

```jsx
import { useState } from 'react';

export default function Home() {
  const [email, setEmail] = useState('');

  const handleSubmit = (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    console.log('Email submitted:', email);
    alert('Thanks for subscribing!');
    setEmail('');
  };

  return (
    <div style={{ textAlign: 'center', padding: '40px' }}>
      <h1>Welcome to Our New Startup!</h1>
      <p>Please subscribe to get the latest updates:</p>
      <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
        <input
          type="email"
          value={email}
          onChange={(e) => setEmail(e.target.value)}
          placeholder="Enter your email"
          required
        />
        <button type="submit">Subscribe</button>
      </form>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Feel free to throw in some inline styles or create a CSS file in `styles` for more flair. Now, about that form – you'll want it hooked to something in production. You could look into:

- Mailchimp for adding to a mailing list.
- SendGrid to handle sending emails.
- Services like Formspree or Getform for endpoint magic without a server.

Deployment time. For Vercel, splash in their CLI if you're not using the dashboard:

```bash
npm install -g vercel
```

Now, deploy. Just run inside your project:

```bash
vercel
```

Follow the prompts; you may need to log in or sign up.

To bring your own domain into play, head over to your Vercel dashboard. Connect your domain to your project and update your DNS settings via your registrar so it points to Vercel. Once that's all set, you should be live with your landing page, all ready for visitors on your new domain.

